                <div class="question-card"><div class="question-text">&ldquo;What do you love most about [Product]?&rdquo;</div><p class="body-sm" style="color:var(--text-muted);">Testimonial mining. Responses become marketing copy and case study material.</p><div class="question-meta"><span class="badge badge-promoter">Open-ended</span><span class="badge badge-source">Always use</span></div></div>
                <div class="question-card"><div class="question-text">&ldquo;Would you be willing to leave us a review?&rdquo;</div><p class="body-sm" style="color:var(--text-muted);">Advocacy conversion. Strike while sentiment is high with a direct review link.</p><div class="question-meta"><span class="badge badge-promoter">Yes/No + Link</span><span class="badge badge-source">Score 9-10</span></div></div>
                <div class="question-card"><div class="question-text">&ldquo;Who else might benefit from [Product]?&rdquo;</div><p class="body-sm" style="color:var(--text-muted);">Referral generation. Promoters generate 7x more positive referrals than detractors.</p><div class="question-meta"><span class="badge badge-promoter">Email/Name</span><span class="badge badge-source">Referral</span></div></div>
                <div class="question-card"><div class="question-text">&ldquo;Can we feature you in a case study?&rdquo;</div><p class="body-sm" style="color:var(--text-muted);">Social proof. Enterprise customers who agree become your strongest sales tool.</p><div class="question-meta"><span class="badge badge-promoter">Yes/No</span><span class="badge badge-source">Enterprise</span></div></div>
                <div class="question-card"><div class="question-text">&ldquo;What made you give us a [score]?&rdquo;</div><p class="body-sm" style="color:var(--text-muted);">Identifies &ldquo;wow&rdquo; moments. Understanding what drives a 10 helps you replicate it.</p><div class="question-meta"><span class="badge badge-promoter">Open-ended</span><span class="badge badge-source">Score = 10</span></div></div>
            </div>
            <blockquote class="geo-passage" style="margin-top:var(--space-8);">
                The most effective NPS follow-up questions are segmented by score range. For Detractors (0-6), ask &ldquo;What would we need to change to improve your score?&rdquo; &mdash; this is future-focused and implies willingness to act. For Passives (7-8), ask &ldquo;What would it take to make you a 9 or 10?&rdquo; &mdash; this targets the highest-ROI conversion, since passives have 2x the lifetime value of detractors. For Promoters (9-10), ask &ldquo;What do you love most?&rdquo; &mdash; this mines testimonial language. Companies using conditional follow-up questions collect 45% more actionable feedback than those using a single follow-up. Keep surveys to 2 questions (score + open text) &mdash; 2-question surveys complete 3.2x more often than 5+ question surveys.
                <span class="cite">Bain &amp; Company; Formbricks data</span>
            </blockquote>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ SECTION 5: NPS METHODOLOGY (NEW) ============ -->
        <section class="section" id="methodology">
            <div class="section-header">
                <p class="overline">Research</p>
                <h2 class="h1">NPS Methodology: What the Research Actually Says</h2>
                <p class="body-lg">A balanced look at NPS &mdash; its origins, limitations, and why it still matters despite academic criticism.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:var(--space-6);">
                <div class="card-feature">
                    <h3 class="h3" style="margin-bottom:var(--space-4);">The Origins</h3>
                    <p style="line-height:1.7;">NPS was introduced by Fred Reichheld in a 2003 Harvard Business Review article, &ldquo;The One Number You Need to Grow,&rdquo; and co-developed with Bain &amp; Company and Satmetrix. The core idea: a single question (&ldquo;How likely are you to recommend?&rdquo;) could predict business growth better than complex satisfaction surveys. By 2020, two-thirds of Fortune 1000 companies had adopted NPS as a key metric. <span class="cite">HBR, 2003; Bain &amp; Company</span></p>
                </div>
                <div class="card-feature">
                    <h3 class="h3" style="margin-bottom:var(--space-4);">What the Critics Say</h3>
                    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:var(--space-4);">
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Declining popularity:</strong> NPS dropped from the 2nd to 8th most popular CX metric between 2023 and 2024, per CMSWire&rsquo;s State of Digital Customer Experience report. <span class="cite">CMSWire, 2024</span></p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Not the best predictor:</strong> Keiningham et al. (2007) demonstrated in the Journal of Marketing that the American Customer Satisfaction Index outperforms NPS as a predictor of growth in 5 of 9 industries studied. A 2022 Journal of Business Research study found that a simple &ldquo;top-box&rdquo; metric (counting only 9-10 scores, no subtraction) outperformed NPS at predicting future sales growth. <span class="cite">Journal of Marketing; JBR, 2022</span></p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>The &ldquo;predict vs. act&rdquo; gap:</strong> 68% of self-reported Promoters never actually make a referral. NPS asks people to predict their future behavior, which is unreliable. <span class="cite">Kumar et al., 2007</span></p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Cultural bias:</strong> Liked companies score -47 NPS in Japan vs +64 in India (XM Institute, n=17,509). Japan has developed an alternative metric (PSJ) because NPS thresholds are culturally invalid there. <span class="cite">XM Institute; Kimura, 2022</span></p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Statistical noise:</strong> An NPS of +50 with only 100 responses has a 95% confidence interval of roughly +30 to +70 &mdash; a 40-point range. Most companies over-react to noise in small samples. <span class="cite">Colin Fraser; MeasuringU</span></p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Incentive inflation:</strong> Offering survey completion incentives inflates NPS by 15-25 points, invalidating any benchmarking. <span class="cite">Journal of Marketing Research</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card-feature">
                    <h3 class="h3" style="margin-bottom:var(--space-4);">Why NPS Still Matters</h3>
                    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:var(--space-3);">
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Simplicity drives adoption.</strong> More complex metrics (ACSI, CES, NEV) have lower organizational buy-in. NPS gets executive attention precisely because it&rsquo;s one number.</p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>Trending over time is valuable.</strong> Even if the absolute score is imperfect, tracking NPS quarterly reveals meaningful patterns &mdash; especially when segmented by cohort.</p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>The follow-up question is the real insight.</strong> The open-text &ldquo;why&rdquo; often generates more actionable data than the numerical score. 82% of respondents answer the follow-up when well-constructed. <span class="cite">InMoment</span></p>
                        <p style="line-height:1.7;"><strong>NPS as a conversation starter.</strong> Use it to open dialogue with customers, not as a final performance judgment. The close-the-loop workflow matters more than the number.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <blockquote class="geo-passage">
                While NPS is the most widely adopted customer loyalty metric, academic research has identified important limitations. Keiningham et al. (2007) published in the Journal of Marketing that NPS was not the single best predictor of business growth, with the American Customer Satisfaction Index outperforming NPS in five of nine industries. A 2022 Journal of Business Research study found that a simple &ldquo;top-box&rdquo; metric outperformed NPS at predicting future sales growth. Kumar et al. (2007) documented that 68% of self-reported Promoters never made a referral. Cultural differences are dramatic &mdash; XM Institute data from 17,509 consumers showed liked companies score -47 NPS in Japan versus +64 in India, leading Japan to develop its own alternative (PSJ). Despite these criticisms, NPS remains valuable because its simplicity drives organizational adoption, longitudinal trending reveals meaningful patterns, and the qualitative follow-up generates more actionable insight than the score itself.
                <span class="cite">Sources: HBR 2003; Keiningham 2007; Kumar 2007; XM Institute; Kimura 2022</span>
            </blockquote>
        </section>

