            </div>
            <div style="max-width:720px; margin:0 auto;">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>What is a good NPS score?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">Any score above 0 means you have more promoters than detractors. Scores above +30 are considered good, above +50 excellent, and above +70 world-class. However, NPS varies dramatically by industry: SaaS averages +41 while internet service providers average +2. Always benchmark against your specific industry, not absolute thresholds.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>How do you calculate NPS?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">NPS = (% Promoters) &minus; (% Detractors). Respondents who score 9-10 are Promoters, 7-8 are Passives, and 0-6 are Detractors. For example, if 60% are Promoters, 25% Passive, and 15% Detractors, your NPS is 60 &minus; 15 = +45. The result ranges from &minus;100 to +100.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>How often should you run NPS surveys?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">For relationship NPS (overall brand health), quarterly is the most common cadence &mdash; frequent enough to track trends, infrequent enough to avoid survey fatigue. For transactional NPS (post-interaction), survey after key events like onboarding, support tickets, or feature launches. Response rates drop 40% after the 3rd survey in 90 days, so enforce cooldown periods.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>What follow-up questions should you ask after NPS?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">Always start with an open-text &ldquo;Why did you give that score?&rdquo; as question #2. Then use conditional logic: ask promoters &ldquo;What do you value most?&rdquo;, passives &ldquo;What would make us a 9 or 10?&rdquo;, and detractors &ldquo;What was your biggest frustration?&rdquo;. Limit total questions to 3-5 to maintain completion rates above 60%.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>What is the difference between relational and transactional NPS?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">Relational NPS measures overall brand loyalty over time &mdash; sent on a schedule (quarterly) to your full customer base. Transactional NPS measures satisfaction with a specific interaction &mdash; triggered after events like onboarding, support tickets, or purchases. Most mature NPS programs run both: relational for strategic trends, transactional for operational improvement. Transactional NPS typically has higher response rates (40-60%) vs relational (15-30%).</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>How many responses do you need for a reliable NPS?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">For &plusmn;5% margin of error at 95% confidence, you need roughly 267 responses. Below 100 responses, NPS has a margin of error exceeding &plusmn;10 points, making trend analysis unreliable. For small audiences, focus on qualitative follow-up data rather than the score itself. Use our sample size calculator above to compute the exact number for your audience.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>Can NPS be negative?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">Yes. NPS ranges from &minus;100 (every respondent is a detractor) to +100 (every respondent is a promoter). A negative NPS means you have more detractors than promoters. Some industries and regions regularly see negative average NPS &mdash; for example, Japan&rsquo;s cultural response style results in an average NPS of &minus;47 across industries, compared to +17 in the US.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>Is NPS still relevant in 2025?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">NPS remains the most widely used customer loyalty metric, though its popularity has dropped from #2 to #8 in Gartner&rsquo;s CX metric rankings since 2018. Critics note it doesn&rsquo;t reliably predict growth (Keiningham et al., 2007) and suffers from cultural bias. However, NPS&rsquo;s simplicity, benchmarkability, and 20+ years of comparative data make it irreplaceable as a starting point. The trend is toward using NPS alongside CSAT, CES, and behavioral metrics rather than as a standalone measure.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>How can you improve your NPS score?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">The fastest path to NPS improvement is closing the loop: companies that contact detractors within 48 hours recover 70% of at-risk accounts and see +23 NPS on average. Beyond that: (1) Fix the top 3 themes from open-text responses, (2) convert passives by asking what would make them a 9, (3) activate promoters as referral sources, (4) survey at the right time &mdash; not when customers are frustrated by an unrelated issue. Structural changes (product improvement, support speed) drive lasting NPS gains; survey optimization alone does not.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                        <span>What&rsquo;s the best channel to send NPS surveys?</span><span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-a"><p class="body-sm">In-app surveys deliver the highest response rates (30-60%) and most contextual data since users are actively engaged. Email works best for relationship NPS at scale (15-30% response rate). SMS achieves 30-45% response rates but inflates NPS by 5-8 points due to channel bias. Link/QR code surveys suit physical touchpoints. The best approach combines channels: in-app for transactional NPS, email for quarterly relationship NPS. Always normalize scores when comparing across channels.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>
